Barack Obama will be the fourth U.S. president to receive the Nobel Peace Prize
U.S. President Barack Obama will arrive in Oslo, Norway to spend 26 hours and receive the Nobel Peace Prize, as the fourth American president in history.
The diploma, medal and check of 1.4 million dollars will receive them, among other things, for the exceptional effort in strengthening world diplomacy and cooperation between nations.
White House chief and his wife Michelle will arrive in the Norwegian metropolis in the morning and have much to do.
First, visit of the Nobel Institute, where for the first time he will meet the five members of the committee that, in October, elected him among 172 people and 33 organizations.
Afterwards, the presidential couple is scheduled to meet with the King of Norway, Harald V, and Queen Sonia.
In the afternoon the visit will culminate with a ceremony in which Obama will receive the prestigious award.
He will be the fourth American president to receive it, even if the third one who receives him in his office.
The White House has already announced that, upon receiving the award, it will talk about the Afghan war.
The President does not want to avoid such an issue, knowing that he is receiving the award as president of a country that is currently at war in two countries.
His war efforts increased further with the sending of additional troops to Afghanistan, which he does not forget to mention any of his critics.
At the ceremony, Obama will also receive the gold medal, diploma and check of ten million Swedish kronor (approximately 24 million Czech kroner).
It is proposed to donate them to charitable paraffins, but has not yet decided which particular organization to do.
During their full program, the President and his wife will participate in a banquet to which the Norwegian kings, the prime minister and another 250 guests will attend.
Obama from the beginning had a rather reserved attitude towards the prize.
He mentioned, for example, having the feeling of not fully deserving of it.
He also repeated several times that the prize is not only for him, but for all those who fight for the same values as him.
Immediately after the announcement he mentioned that it represents "a challenge to take action."
