U.S.: Repetition is the mother of wisdom
It is comic that Barack Obama, the president with the reputation of the smartest man, as a diligent student repeats in the Afghan question the strategy of his predecessor, whom he himself took for the dumbest.
When he finally revealed his Afghan approach, eagerly awaiting, it was shown to be a copy of the script used for Iraq by Bush, created three years ago.
Not only in the same text is the “as in Iraq” locution used several times, but he also did not hesitate to use the title of the January 2007 Bush declaration for his own statement: “A new way forward.”
It was he himself, who three years ago criticized Bush’s idea of sending new military reinforcements to Iraq, the country that is suffering from the civil war. And that he criticized it as "an irresponsible decision and with catastrophic consequences."
The following months, however, showed that Bush’s strategy, based on the recommendations of field captains, was the only possible and successful, so that today there is nothing talk of Iraq in the news.
Bush’s reputation did not improve, however objectively he left his successor a much more favorable initial situation than expected.
In Afghanistan, Barack Obama hopes the miracle will be repeated.
The field captains again asked him to increase the military contingent, especially the commander-in-chief of the Afghan operation General Stanley McCristal. He, even despite traditional subordinate relations, subjected undecided riflemen in the White House to harsh criticism.
He asked 40,000 men to improve the situation.
The president faltered for three months, but he didn’t think of anything better, so at least he tricked the general into 10,000 military personnel.
He managed to get Europe to promise him another 5,000, although he himself previously had at least 10,000.
The most problematic thing about Obama’s entire strategy seems his goal, to start withdrawing troops from Afghanistan in 18 months and finish this procedure in three years. The entire doctrine of Obama generated more questions from the answers he offered.
Many doubt that the increase will bear the same fruit as the procedure in Iraq.
Despite the fratricidal wars in recent years, Iraq’s society is relatively well organized, its leaders respect the agreements.
The situation in Afghanistan is different: it is not possible to trust anyone and no agreement is fulfilled.
Under these conditions it is difficult to prepare the Afghan security forces, if they are accustomed to changing the boss every day according to their needs.
Political institutions, though formally established, will remain only one people of Potemkin. Behind him will remain the patriarchal tribal relations.
Balancing the interests of different ethnic groups is extraordinarily complicated due to confusing relations, even more complicated by Pakistani and Iranian influences.
Not even establishing a state that is “able to act,” a minimum goal of the entire operation, it seems very real.
The horizon of Obama’s strategy clashes over his voluntarism.
For the past eight years, the situation in Afghanistan has continued to worsen and is now about to break out.
Only a romantic soul, who knows nothing of reality, can believe that the military sent to war to "return home soon" will perform some miracle here.
From the political point of view, setting the date of the withdrawal of the troops is pure irresponsibility, since the Taliban will consider it an indirect declaration of the American defeat.
The last NATO summit showed that Europeans are increasingly underwilling to participate in military operations in Afghanistan.
European politicians do not know, and they also do not want to explain to their constituents what relationship is the security of Germany or Italy with the war with the Hindu Kush.
The other factor, capable of radically affecting the situation, is the development of events in Iran.
If the situation continues to worsen and the increased sanctions have no effect on the Iranians, the U.S. will have to make a difficult decision: try to solve the problem with military force or not.
It will be necessary to look for answers precisely when, according to Obama, America begins the triumphant withdrawal of troops from Afghanistan.
However, each solution like this will mean a dramatic setback for the Afghan situation.
The only positive point for Barack Obama is the fact that three years are missing for the presidential election and that is why there is still a long time to find another strategy, if this is a total failure.
