Top executives at U.S. bank Goldman Sachs will not receive cash bonuses this year.
The entity announced it to react to the harsh criticism of its salary practices.
The group of 30 senior managers will receive, instead of money, shares that cannot be sold within a minimum period of five years.
In addition, the actions may be withdrawn if they have taken excessive risks.
According to Reuters, Goldman Sachs thus became the leader in the effort to bring bonuses together on Wall Street with long-term power.
I suppose Wall Street is fully aware of the longest road it must undertake, said former JPMorgan investor banker Douglas Elliott.
The problem is in the details, he added.
The Goldman Sachs bank faced criticism after having taken almost 17,000 million dollars (almost 300,000 million CZK) for the bonuses, in the first three quarters of this year.
The total sum of the bonuses in the entity for this year, according to the Reuters agency, probably exceeds, despite the measure announced today, the 20,000 million dollars.
The high bonuses in the banking sector became, with the arrival of the financial crisis, a sensitive issue in politics.
Britain announced on Wednesday that it plans to tax at one time, with a tax of fifty percent, the bonuses for bankers exceeding 25,000 pounds (about 712,000 CZK).
France is also preparing similar measures.
This year women received the Nobel Prizes in all the categories but Physics
Five women, which is a record figure, received today in Stockholm from King Charles XVI Gustav of Sweden the Nobel Prizes this year, in specialized categories and in literature.
In addition to the four scientists, she was also among the winners of a German writer of Romanian origin, Herta Müller.
The Nobel Prize in medicine was awarded two American biologists, Elizabeth Blackburn and Carol Greider, as well as their compatriot Jack Szostak for research in the field of chromosomes.
The Nobel Prize in chemistry was received by Israeli Ada Jonath and Americans Venkatraman Ramakrishna and Thomas Steitz for explaining the structure and function of ribosomes.
The last prize awarded, the Nobel Prize in Economics, was received by the American Elinor Ostrom and his compatriot Oliver Williamson for the analysis of an economic report.
The only specialized category, without an award-winning woman, was Physics.
This award was received today by scientists Charles Kao for research in the field of optical cables, and George Smith with Willard Boyle for the invention of the CCD chip, which forms the basis of all digital cameras, faxes or telescopes.
Each awardee collected the diploma, the Nobel medal and the certificate of money received.
This sum in each category is up to ten million Swedish kronor (about 25 million Czech kronor).
In the case of several winners in each category, the prize is distributed to each other.
