The secret of the splendor over Norway resolved: the Russians tested a missile
A special luminous effect of unknown origin was observed on Norway.
The Russian Defense Ministry ended up acknowledging yesterday that near the borders with Norway it tested a ballistic intercontinental missile.
The launch failed again. The "Bulava"-type missile, formerly destined to be the pride of the Russian army, is becoming the nightmare of Russian generals and Prime Minister Vladimir Putin.
Not even his repeated presence in the missile tests has had the desired effect on the success of test flights.
Bulavah, in most cases, did not fly out or an air failure occurred.
In Russian newspapers they write of "Bulavah" as "a missile that does not fly."
A missile that doesn't fly, but shines.
During this, the 13th test, no problem occurred at the beginning.
At the end of the flight, technical problems occurred again in the aircraft.
The engine probably exploded in the third stage of the missile.
This time "Bulava" was launched from the nuclear submarine Dmitry Donskoy, which floated submerged in the White Sea.
This type of missile allows the launch from a boat that is moving and is submerged at the same time.
That’s why it’s likely that the mysterious light over Norway, caused by an unidentified flying object, was actually the failed “Bulavah.”
The Norwegians did not hesitate from the first moment onwards that it was a Russian missile.
The generals this time defend themselves by stating that one cannot simply speak of a failure.
The first two stages of the missile held out and the breakdown occurred in the third.
In the previous cases the engines were immediately broken down in the first stage.
Although none of the launches went completely without errors, according to the management of the Ministry of Defense only six of the thirteen were unsuccessful.
The success of almost fifty percent full of optimism to the generals and that is why they continue to affirm that "Bulavah" one day will fly without problems and that it will even manage to carry up to ten nuclear hypersonic blocks, whose maximum total weight is 1.15 tons.
