Hyundai met the requirements of the unions. It will cancel all supplementary work
The management of the automobile factory in Nošovice agreed with the unions to cancel all supplementary work.
Precisely because of the frequent supplementary work, the unions declared the emergency on Monday by strike.
The information was confirmed by Petr Vaněk, the spokesman for the Hyundai automobile factory.
The management, however, wants for this year to agree with the unions one more Saturday shift.
We cannot resign ourselves to our manufacturing plan, as it is essential. That is why we proposed voluntary supplementary work for Saturday, December 19, that is, two shifts will be worked, Vaněk said.
According to the Sedmička.cz server, the company offered a 400 CZK bonus to employees working Saturday shift.
The bonus will also be paid for last Saturday, November 28.
According to Vaňka, the company decided to change the way it motivates its employees with the additional work offered.
Employees can charge the bonus for overtime or they can take a day off on December 28, that is, prolong on a Christmas day, Vaněk said.
In addition, all Saturday shift employees will receive money for the trip and for the food.
Because the supplementary work was the most urgent and problematic point of the comments and complaints of the trade unionists and strikers, who stopped the manufacture last week, the management yesterday afternoon immediately decided to cancel all the supplementary work for the month of December, Vaněk said.
Employees at the auto factory were forced to work two more hours in addition to eight-hour shifts and this situation lasted virtually every day until last week.
After signing the agreement, the unions will cancel the strike emergency.
Another negotiation between the management of the factory and the trade unionists must be held on Monday morning.
Union chief Petr Kuchař said on Wednesday that if they committed to meeting the requirements and signing the document, they are willing to cancel the strike emergency.
The situation at the auto factory worsened last week on Wednesday, when about 400 employees spontaneously went on strike for frequent supplementary work.
They also protested against poor payment terms and alleged harassment.
The management said employees had to work overtime to meet the requirements and be able to supply the cars.
The unionists in their declaration of the emergency by strike on Monday, also demanded that none of the employees, who last Wednesday interrupted the manufacture, be penalized in any way.
With regard to supplementary work, trade unions require that the company reduce it to a minimum.
In addition, this year they require a remuneration of 5,000 kroner for this work.
The car factory in Nošovice Hyundai currently has 2,000 employees.
Serial manufacturing was started last November.
As of last September, it manufactured approximately 80,000 cars; its current productive potential is 200,000 cars a year.
A Czech discovery: an effective substance even in the 'calliced' HIV virus
The team of Czech and German scientists tests new compounds capable of moderating the spread of HIV in the body
The main advantage of this improved substance is the fact that it is also effective against drug-resistant viruses.
In some cases this is more important than the fact that the compound is not as effective in a common variant of the virus, such as some accessible drugs already.
AIDS disease cannot be cured until now.
However, the lives of patients can be significantly prolonged thanks to a mixture of drugs that prevent the replication of the HIV virus in the body.
However, its use has many side effects.
If the replication of the virus is not completely suppressed, the so-called resistant viruses will be created; against them, the drugs no longer work.
The work of the experts of three Institutes of the Czech Academy of Sciences, VŠCHT Prague and the University of Heidelberg demonstrates the possibility of mastering the resistance of the virus.
They showed that substances called metallocarborans have an effect on albumin, responsible for the spread of the HIV virus.
Metallocarbones are composed of boron, hydrogen, carbon and cobalt.
These compounds block the spread of the virus in a different way to all the drugs used today, and that is why they can solve the problem of resistance.
In their work the scientists find new, ‘improved’ compounds, prepared knowing the molecular mechanism of their binding to virus albumin.
Metallocarbones have a single three-dimensional structure: two polyhedron cages composed of boron, hydrogen and carbon atoms are joined by the metal atom, in this case by cobalt.
A traitorous and resistant virus
HIV proteasis is an albumin of the HIV virus, and is essential for the life cycle of the virus.
