The pneumococal vaccine will be free and voluntary
The pneumococal vaccine from January will put an end to the usual customs.
As a first vaccine it must be free for families and at the same time voluntary.
However, opinions already appear, that the mandatory vaccine would be more effective.
Preparations for the introduction of the free pneumococcal vaccine culminate.
The Institute of Medicines is already setting the maximum prices for vaccines, which will be covered by insurance companies.
Experts are also already clear in the vaccination procedure.
The new vaccine
Free vaccinations for children born in August
From January, children born since August 2 of last year will be able to receive the pneumococal vaccine free of charge.
The condition is not to have received a dose of the vaccine before.
Those who started the vaccine last year or earlier have to cover other doses of the vaccine as well.
The first dose of the vaccine has to be received between the third and fifth month of age of a child.
Last year, a quarter of families voluntarily let their children be vaccinated against pneumococcus.
The parents, however, paid for a dose of 1600 kroner and more.
To vaccinate younger children, four doses are needed.
Experts generally estimate that insurance companies will spend on vaccines from 300 to 450 thousand kroner annually.
However, they will save on treatment, which is needed for unvaccinated children.
So far the state spent approximately 500 thousand annually for the entire vaccination of the children.
The covered vaccination was initiated by the so-called Janota package.
Pneumococcus is the cause of otitis media, but also of serious infections including meningitis and sepsis.
Of the pneumococal infections in our country every year, 28 children not older than 10 years of age die according to research in hospitals.
In addition to the Czech Republic, the pneumococal vaccine cover in children was introduced in approximately 40 countries.
Will the vaccine be mandatory?
However, at the same time opinions appear, that this vaccine could be mandatory in the future.
From January it must be covered by insurance and voluntary companies.
The mandatory vaccine would be better, said Rudolf Kalovský, the head of the Nahlas civic association.
Their association has long propagated pneumococcal vaccines.
Experts at an international conference, in which our association participated, were not completely satisfied with the fact that we have the voluntary vaccine.
It is not completely ideal.
On the other hand we are happy, to achieve at least this.
I think this is the path we now have to take, Kalovský said.
The Ministry of Health however does not want to change the procedure of vaccination against pneumococcus.
At this time we do not think about it at all, said its spokesman Vlastimil Sršeň.
