He was one of more than 6,000 volunteers who gathered Saturday morning to place crowns on veterans’ graves in various sections of Arlington Cemetery.
In 1992, Morrill Worcester, the owner of the Worcester Crown Company in Harrington, Maine, kicked off the event when he and other people decided to decorate several hundred graves in Arlington Cemetery.
In what is already an 18-year tradition, Morrill and his wife Karen make the trip every year stopping in different cities along the way, to officiate events dedicated to military and victims of terrorism.
The Worcesters also founded a nonprofit organization, Wreaths Across America, that has extended the event to other states.
This year volunteers placed more than 16,000 crowns on the graves of Arlington Cemetery, areas in the Pentagon, graves at Fayetteville National Cemetery in Arkansas, Battery Park in New York City, and at the United Airlines Flight 93 memorial site in Shanksville, Pennsylvania.
For the second year, the Walmart Foundation donated more than US$150,000 to purchase and transport the crowns.
Charles Hunt, 70, of Westminster, said she made the trip to Arlington in honor of her husband, a late military career.
As long as her husband is not buried in Arlington, Hunt said this was his way of giving a retribution to those who made sacrifices.
This is a modest way civilians can support our troops, he said.
It's like visiting a family grave.
Wrapped in layers of warm clothing, the volunteers walked through the cemetery’s wide meadows and hills.
Volunteers headed to older graves of World War I, World War II, and the Vietnam War, because they don’t get as many visits as the new graves, organizers said.
The atmosphere was cheerful as the children played and the pairs held hands, while carrying the fresh pine to the tombstones.
Each circular crown was of a deep green, with a small red bow tied on top.
Nearby, Section 60, where most veterans of the Iraq and Afghanistan wars are buried, were virtually silent.
The United Service Organizations donated 1,000 kroner to decorate the section, but the bleak atmosphere of the current wars invaded the area.
People cried openly, others prayed, and families and friends leaned on each other in the glacial air.
Some read loudly sculpted names on the stones, while others bowed to see small black and white plates placed inside the wet mud, for those whose gravestones have not yet been completed.
Sandra Lockwood was one of many mothers who wiped away the tears from her eyes in front of her son’s grave.
