Cuban officials arrested a U.S. government contractor
The Cuban government has detained a U.S. government contractor who was distributing mobile phones and laptops in the country, State Department officials said Saturday.
The contractor, who has not yet been identified, works for Development Alternatives Inc, based in Bethesda.
The company works on projects for clients such as the U.S. Agency for International Development and the World Bank.
Consular officers along with the U.S. Interests Section in Havana are seeking access to the detainee, who was arrested on Dec. 5.
The specific charges have not been made public, although under Cuban law, a Cuban citizen or a foreign visitor can be detained for almost anything that is considered "dangerous."
All so-called counter-revolutionary activities, including mild protests and critical writings, pose the risk of arrest.
Anti-government graffiti and speeches are considered serious crimes.
Cuba has a fledgling blogger community, led by popular commentator Yoani Sanchez, who often writes about how she and her husband are followed and harassed by government agents.
Sanchez has repeatedly applied for permission to leave the country to accept prizes, but the permit has been denied.
The arrest of a U.S. contractor may likely provoke tensions between the Castro brothers’ communist government in Cuba and the Obama administration, which has been seeking a “slow-paced” rapprochement to improve relations with the island.
The New York Times was the first to release the news of the arrest Friday night.
The new U.S. policy emphasizes that if the Cuban government takes concrete steps, such as the release of political prisoners and the creation of more space for the opposition, there will be reciprocity on the part of the United States.
Mobile phones and laptops are legal in Cuba, even if they are new and coveted products in a country where the average salary of a government worker is 15 dollars per month.
The Cuban government granted ordinary citizens the right to buy mobiles only this year; they are mostly used for texting, as a 15-minute phone conversation would cost the daily salary.
Internet use is extremely limited on the island.
It is available in expensive hotels and for foreign visitors to the hotel, and in some government establishment, such as universities.
Cubans who want to connect often have to give their names to the government.
Access to many websites is restricted.
The arrest of an American in Cuba is unusual.
Gloria Berbena, a press officer in the U.S. Interests Section in Havana, said most of the handful of U.S. citizens in jail in Cuba are behind bars for crimes such as drug trafficking.
Berbena said he could not provide further information about the arrest.
Arrest and detention are clearly wrong.
An activity that in any other open society would be legal, such as distributing free mobiles, in Cuba is a crime, said José Miguel Vivanco, director of the program of the Americas of the organization Human Rights Watch, which recently published a hard report on freedoms in Cuba, called "Nuevo Castro, same Cuba", a reference to the location of Raúl Castro as leader of the country, to replace his sickly older brother Fidel.
Vivanco said the defendants are often detained, prosecuted and imprisoned in a day.
He said that any solution would probably be political, and that the Cuban government often provokes a negative reaction in the United States, just as the two countries begin to have more dialogue.
