Drafted in the country’s constitution in 1978, China’s one-child policy is arguably the most controversial mandate introduced to date by the Communist Party.
Couples who violate the policy face huge fines, up to three times their annual pay in some areas, and employment discrimination.
Chinese officials have backed the policy for their contribution to avoid critical pressure on their natural resources, while human rights defenders have denounced abuses in the imposition of policy.
In rural areas, some officials have forced pregnant women with a second child to undergo abortions.
In addition, many couples have done abortions according to the sex of the fetus, leading to a high unnatural male-female ratio.
In recent years, demographic officials have gradually softened their stance on one-child policy.
In 2004, they allowed for more exceptions to the rule, including urban residents, members of ethnic minorities and cases in which both husband and wife are only children, and in 2007 they mitigated many of their hardline slogans.
Qiao Xiaochun, a professor at the Beijing University Demographic Research Institute, said central government officials have recently been debating even more radical changes, such as allowing couples to have two children if one of the spouses is an only child.
In July, Shanghai became the first Chinese city to launch an aggressive campaign to incentivize more births.
Almost overnight, the posters ordering families to have a single child were replaced by copies of regulations detailing who would be suitable for having a second child and how to apply for a permit.
The city government sent family planning officials and volunteers to visit couples in their homes and slide leaflets under the doors.
It has also promised to provide emotional and financial guidance to those who have chosen to have more than one child.
Family planning officials say the response has been very unoverwhelming.
Disappointing response
Although officials in a rural city on the outskirts of Shanghai argue that they saw a moderate increase in requests from couples who want a second child after the campaign launch, the more urban districts indicate no change.
The municipality of Huinan, with a population of 115,000, for example, is still receiving only four to five applications per month.
The disappointed Shanghai officials say that, despite the campaign, the number of births in the city in 2010 is still expected to only reach around 165,000, slightly higher than in 2009, but lower than in 2008.
Feng Juying, head of the family planning committee of Caolu Township in Shanghai, said financial considerations are probably the main reason why many people don’t want more children.
They want to give their first child their best, he said.
Yang Jiawei, 27, and his wife, Liu Juanjuan, 26, said they would love to have two children and are legally empowered to do so.
But like many Chinese, they have only insufficient health and life insurance provided by the government.
Without a social safety net, they argue, that option would be irresponsible.
People in the West incorrectly see the one-child policy as a matter of rights, said Yang, a construction engineer whose wife is seven months pregnant with the couple’s first child.
Yeah, we're being robbed of having more than one child.
But the problem is not just a political issue.
It's the money.
Other couples cite psychological reasons for their doubts.
Wang, the HR manager, said he wants an only child because she was, too: "We were the center of our families and we were used to everyone taking care of us.
We are not used to taking care of others and we really do not want to take care of others. "
Chen Zijian, 42, owner of a translation agency, explained it more forcefully.
For parents with two middle-class careers, which reduce the birth rate, he said, it’s about being successful enough to be selfish.
People between the ages of 20 and 30 grew up seeing their parents struggle during the first days of China’s experiment with capitalism and they don’t want that kind of life for themselves, he said.
Even a single child is time-consuming by the parents, he said.
A mother has to give up at least two years of her social life.
Then there are issues of space, "they have to remodel their apartment", and the strategic "has to have a curriculum prepared for the best day care when the child is 9 months old."
Most of his friends are willing to face this once, Chen said, but not two.
