We don't want to make too many sacrifices.
UN group outlines plan to reduce emissions
The UN-sponsored climate conference, characterized so far by challenging stances and mutual recriminations, captured renewed attention on Friday with the release of a document that foresees ambitious reductions in greenhouse gases over the next 40 years, with industrialized nations carrying most of the burden on their shoulders in the short term.
The text, which could provide the basis for a final political agreement to regulate greenhouse gases, highlighted the remaining obstacles and highlighted the way forward.
But it was seen as a major breakthrough in a negotiation that is running out of time, with more than 100 world leaders coming to Copenhagen next week.
Crafted by an ad hoc UN working group, the text does not talk about how much money rich countries would give the poor to tackle global warming in the short and long term.
And this offers a variety of options for key questions, including how developed economies and major emerging economies would cut their coal production, and what the limit of the global temperature rise would be that political strategists would be willing to tolerate.
This gives a lot of flexibility to the process, said John Coequyt, a senior representative in Washington for the Sierra Club.
Michael Zammit Cutajar, who drafted the six-page document, summarized a 180-page negotiating text to focus on what the UN’s top climate official, Yvo de Bóer, described as “the big picture.”
It shows the profiles for a possible agreement, in which industrialized nations would collectively cut their emissions by 2020 by 25 to 45 percent, compared to 1990 levels, while major developing countries would reduce their emissions over the same period by 15 to 30 percent.
Together, countries would cut emissions by 50 to 95 percent by 2050.
The European Union also spurred the talks on Friday, promising to provide US$3.6 billion annually over the next three years, to help poorer countries adapt to the impact of climate change, from floods and droughts to deforestation.
Anyway, on Friday the same kind of verbal fireworks that have dominated the conversations last week was presented.
U.S. special climate envoy Todd Stern rejected claims calling for mandatory greenhouse gas emission cuts for industrialized countries, compared to volunteers from major emerging economies, if they were not funded by the developed world.
The maneuver indicated that the Obama administration is taking a tougher line with China, with respect to what Bush administration officials did just two years ago.
The United States will not make an agreement without major developing countries moving forward and taking action, said Stern, who also regretted that the text did not do enough to ensure that the cuts could be verified by outside observers.
Stern made his comments an hour after Chinese Deputy Foreign Minister He Yafei claimed that the top U.S. climate negotiator lacked “common sense,” or was “very irresponsible” for saying earlier in the week that the United States would not help China economically cope with global warming.
With the future economic trajectory of the world’s major powers at stake, fault lines have erupted both within the developing world, as well as between the industrial world and emerging economies.
The current battle is both to save individual economies and to save the planet, with China and the United States facing their respective obligations, while the poorest nations insist that the twenty-four most influential countries in the world are ignoring the scientific imperative to take the bravest action.
Ricardo Ulate, a delegate from Costa Rica, said it’s not surprising that major powers are discussing who should pay for spending to limit greenhouse gases, even though vulnerable countries have become more aggressive seeking to contain the big emitters responsible for their actions.
This is clearly a game where a new economic hegemony is being developed, said Ulate, who also works as a regional advisor on climate change for Mexico and Central America, for International Conservation.
Some of the countries most vulnerable to the impact of climate change indicated that they would continue to push for a legally mandatory treaty in Copenhagen, although most of the main participants say the talks will produce a political agreement at most.
The Alliance of Small Island States, which has 43 members, drew up a 24-page preliminary treaty proposal early Friday morning.
Artur Runge-Metzger, who is leading international climate negotiations on behalf of the European Commission, said the push of small island nations has "putted political pressure on the entire political process," in part because they are now unified and demand action from emerging economies such as China and India.
The talks took on a new urgency as delegates focused on the fact that they must resolve most of the exceptional issues before the heads of government come to close a deal.
Senior officials, such as Indian Environment Minister Jairam Ramesh and the Chinese deputy minister, descended from the planes and rushed into the halls of the Bella Center, to closed-door meetings and press conferences, so that they could delimit the claims that will be arbitrated over the next week.
The absolute disorder of the meeting (where every day 13,000 people enter and leave the convention center, the activists who play the guitar present nightly shows mocking the countries that they say are selling, and preliminary proposals are passed hand in hand instead of via mail), poses a challenge.
The intensity only builds: almost all key ministers are here right now, and on Wednesday 60 heads of government will be in Copenhagen.
We are entering the major leagues, said Carlos Manuel Rodriguez, vice president for global Conservation Policy International.
Heavyweights are coming.
