Management or end of business intelligence?
If nothing changes in the management of large French companies, our struggle for the development of business intelligence will have been in vain...
More than ten years ago, the attitude of the management of large companies with respect to their employees recalls the position of companies with respect to consumers before the marketing revolution: it is that collaborators adhere to "values" determined from above as before it was to impose on consumers products designed by factory technicians.
By putting the customer at the center of the company, the marketing revolution gave its place to the strategies of conquest of the markets ... although the authoritarian temptation to impose products that have no relation to the preference factors of the customers is repeated regularly.
A demobilization of employees may end in deadly demoralization.
Suicides at France Telecom, PSA or Renault are just the tip of the iceberg of a much more general phenomenon that particularly affects executives.
This demobilization seriously compromises the development of all the intellectual functions of the company, especially R&D and, even more, business intelligence.
Indeed, the Business Intelligence (BI) "demands that all parties involved ... have proactive conduct and a forward-looking vision"; it requires on the part of employees a commitment that is entirely opposed to the recommendations of an authoritarian leadership.
For this reason, we call for a management revolution, which would consist of putting employees at the center of the company’s concerns as well as the client.
Internal opinion polls have relative utility
Will internal opinion polls, such as the questionnaire conducted by Orange among its employees, prompt the management revolution in practice?
Unfortunately, I'm afraid not.
-In principle, because I was able to verify that, in the face of a new situation, and after many laps, all the companies end up doing essentially... what they always did! B989
Secondly, because authoritarianism, one of the pathologies of power, grows proportionately to the importance of its own failures.
Finally, because most managers have a simplistic view of human behavior.
As they come from the great engineering schools, they interpret psychology in a mechanistic way.
They adopt, for intellectual comfort, the ancient behavioral theory that American “neurosciences” recently reactivated, and that the Institutes of Studies and the media spread widely behind their backs.
In this way, by suggesting that it is possible to manage the "commands" (sic) of the executives' commitment, a recent research by Ipsos published in Le Figaro.fr reaffirms the managers in a mechanistic management position, misfit from the world today.
Identifying and measuring mobilisation factors
On the contrary, the management revolution necessary for the proper functioning of modern companies, involves adopting a finalist vision of human behavior.
It consists of integrating in all reasoning or business management practice, a fundamental fact: for employees, commitment to the company is only possible if it appears clearly as a means to make part of their dreams, ambitions and projects a reality.
Today, only studies from the Motifunctional Analysis adopt this conception of employee motivations.
The studies showed that they judge their company based on a predetermined doxa that allows them, through the image they have of the company, to evaluate what it offers them to achieve their own life projects.
Thanks to the identification and measurement of mobilization factors, business managers can control, anticipate and anticipate their "social performance" and relocate human resources management "in place".
In this way, they create a favorable terrain for the organized development of strong and effective business intelligence.
