Turkish justice dissolves pro-Kurdish party, a decision with serious consequences
The Turkish Constitutional Court ruled on Friday in favor of the dissolution of the country’s main pro-Kurdish party, a decision that immediately sparked demonstrations of anger in the Kurdish community, in the Southeast of the country and in Istanbul.
This decision could greatly complicate the task of the government, which has just reached out to the Kurdish community trying to end 25 years of conflict.
The Democratic Society (DTP) party was dissolved because it had become the "focus of activities that harmed the independence of the state and its indivisible unity," the president of the Court, Hasim Kiliç, told reporters after four days of deliberations.
The decision of the 11 judges was unanimous, although only a majority of seven votes were needed to obtain the dissolution, Kiliç said, adding that 37 of the party leaders, among which are its president Ahmet Türk and the deputy Aysel Tugluk, are removed from political life for five years.
The judge also announced the cessation of parliamentary immunity enjoyed by Türk and Tugluk, and the confiscation of the party's assets by the Treasury.
The DTP has 21 seats in Parliament (out of 550).
Its leaders warned before the verdict that MPs would leave Parliament before they were parliamentarians without a party label.
The decision comes in the wake of a proceeding launched by Supreme Court Prosecutor Abdurrahman Yalçinkaya in 2007, which accuses the DTP of obeying the "principles" of the Kurdistan Workers' Party (PKK), considered a terrorist organization by Ankara and many more countries.
Many observers believe the DTP is the legal political showcase of the PKK rebels.
However, the party says it has no "organic links" to the PKK, but refuses to call it a terrorist organization and calls on the government to negotiate with it.
The court’s verdict intervenes at the moment when the government reaches out to the Kurdish community by proposing a series of measures that strengthen their rights, so that the Kurds stop supporting the PKK and thus end the conflict.
DTP leaders said a dissolution could lead to escalation of tensions in Southeast Anatolius, where a large number of demonstrations against the conditions of detention of PKK chief Abdullah Öcalan degenerated into clashes with police in recent weeks.
Since the announcement of justice, thousands of protesters gathered in front of the DTP premises in Diyarbakir, the great city of the Southeast populated mostly by Kurds.
Law enforcement threw tear grenades and used water cannons, while protesters dropped Molotov bombs or slings.
In Istanbul, approximately one hundred people were also concentrated.
Following the verdict, Türk said the justice decision would "deepen the discouragement."
Turkey cannot resolve this issue (Kurdish, NDLR) by dissolving a party, he told reporters.
The government, formed by a party from the Islamist movement, also regrets the decision.
At first, we are opposed to the closure of parties.
This is not how anything is resolved, said Energy Minister Taner Yildiz.
This decision completely boycotts the democratic openness launched by the government, said political analyst Ahmet Insel.
We can expect, of course, a reaction from the PKK, he added.
On Thursday, the PKK was staged an attack that killed seven soldiers three days earlier in northern Turkey, one of the bloodiest attacks in recent months.
