The Cradle of the Dinosaur
The Tawa found looked like many other carnivorous dinosaurs: a two-meter-long, 1.50-meter-high animal that ran over the two strong hind legs, had an elongated head with sharp, curved teeth, short arms with sickle-shaped claws and a long tail.
If the species had lived a couple of million years later, it would not have been something special.
But the Tawa found was one of the first dinosaurs with these body characteristics, reports Sterling Nesbitt of the University of Texas at Austin and colleagues in Thursday’s journal Science.
The species lived around 215 million years ago in what is now New Mexico, which at the time was in a dry area of the supercontinent Pangea in the equator.
Tawa opened a new window into the early evolution of dinosaurs, Nesbitt says.
It shows us a lot about the genealogical relationships, the propagation and characteristics of the early dinosaurs.
Nesbitt and other paleontologists began an excavation at Ghost Ranch in northern New Mexico in 2006.
Sometimes, we’ve found in a day a dozen dinosaur bones, this is unprecedented for Triassic sediments, reports Randall Irmis, a member of the Utah Museum of Natural History team.
The researchers quickly identified some bones as belonging to a new species.
In the course of the excavation they gathered the remains of five specimens in total.
A finding confirms theories about the ancient history of dinosaurs
The name "Tawa" comes from the sun god of the Hopi Indians.
For Sterling Nesbitt it is an exceptional find: "Triassic dinosaur fossils are extremely rare, usually only individual fragments are found."
Other dinosaur experts do not fully share such enthusiasm.
This finding is not particularly spectacular, but it confirms some theories about the ancient history of dinosaurs, says Martin Sander of the University of Bonn.
According to the current current opinion, dinosaurs first appeared about 230 million years ago.
But many of the oldest fossils are incomplete, so the classification of these early dinosaurs is quite controversial.
Thus, experts discuss, for example, when the saurians were divided into their three most important genealogical lineages: the carnivorous theropods among which are the Tyrannosaurus Rex, the Velociraptor and also the birds, the quadrupeda sauropods known as "long neck" and their relatives, and the Herbivorous Ornithishia (the herbivorous ornithishia)and Stegosaurus.
According to the analysis of Nesbitt and his colleagues, Tawa can is a primitive theropod.
This shows an interesting combination of primitive and progressive properties, Nesbitt says.
For example, in the skull of Tawa found the researchers found indications of air pockets, such as those also possessed by the descendants of the theropods, birds.
Thanks to air pockets, the respiration of birds is more efficient than that of mammals.
In the case of Tawa, the bones of the spine were also evidently partially filled with air.
Tawa is the theropod with older and more primitive airbags, says Randall Irmis.
Because the related line of the posterior giant sauropods also possessed air pockets and light bones, it was likely that the common ancestors of both groups already produced this useful innovation.
At least three waves of migration to North America
Because the most primitive dinosaurs hitherto known lived in South America, researchers deduce that the saurias first emerged there.
Consequently, the three genealogical lineages were initially separated and spread from South America through all corners of the Earth, which at that time still formed a single landmass, the supercontinent Pangea.
However, the facts say the team found along with Tawa find the remains of two other theropods not very closely related.
All three cannot descend from a unique related predecessor, the researchers argue.
We believe that at least three migratory waves were given to North America, says Alan Turner of the American Museum of Natural History in New York, co-author of the Science study.
Naturally, there are also opponents.
An even older species, Silesaurus, belonging to a sister group of dinosaurs, lived in present-day Poland, says Bonn paleontologist Martin Sander.
His opinion could give a distorted image, because simply in South America many dinosaur fossils continue to be preserved, while on other continents there is hardly anything to discover.
The question of how dinosaurs managed to evolve from a relatively rare collateral line of reptiles to the dominant terrestrial vertebrates of the Mesozoic remains an enigma.
Meanwhile, in the Triassic dinosaurs still shared their living space with many other reptiles, for example with the ancestors of today’s crocodiles and pterosaurs and with many other saurians.
Towards the end of the Triassic dinosaurs expanded around the world and many new species developed, while kinship became extinct at the boundary of the Triassic towards the Jurassic.
The success stories were not eternal
There are two hypotheses to explain this change, says Martin Sander.
There may have been a mass extinction to which the dinosaurs survived by chance, but the other reptiles did not.
Or the dinosaurs were better adapted, so they were able to beat the opponents in the area.
Successful stories are not always eternal.
150 million years later, a meteorite impact slows the rise of a group of species, which had also already evolved in the Triassic and since then had a miserable existence: mammals.
