Dream worlds
In a state of vigil, some people see images and hear voices that others do not see or hear.
Not only in the case of the mentally ill and in the drug addicts, the boundaries between imagination and reality vanish.
As long as it happens during sleep, everything is in order.
When we are lying in our dark rooms with our eyes closed, we can unhindered the wildest imaginations and creations of fantasy.
However, whoever experiences sleep-like states during wakefulness, or sees and hears things that others do not see or hear, is considered most of the time in the modern Western world as crazy or drug addict, or at least as a maniac.
But such images and voices not only arise in the mentally ill or the drugged.
The fault has our imagination: the same neural processes that allow us to design houses, paint paintings or write novels, sometimes make the boundaries between sleep, madness and reality blur.
Onirically modified states of alert consciousness can appear in the most diverse forms, at best we call them visions, and in the worst, madness.
Although the triggers and effects can be distinguished, the visions of the mystic Hildegard von Bingen, the psychedelic experiences of the New Age prophet Carlos Castañeda, the states of shamanic possession, and psychoses and hallucinations, can be referred to similar processes.
Hallucinations or delusions arise when the balance of neuronal communication substances in the brain – especially dopamine, noradrenaline, serotonin and acetylcholine – has been derailed and the interaction between various parts of it is disturbed.
During a schizophrenic psychosis very often complex hallucinations and crazed thoughts appear.
Gravity no longer has power over him
The relationship between madness and sleep has occupied philosophers and physicians since ancient times.
Aristotle conceived hallucinations as a form of waking sleep, Wilhelm Griesinger, one of the founders of modern psychiatry, observed in 1861 a "great similarity of the state of madness with the dream states", for Sigmund Freud, the dream was even "a psychosis, with all the nonsense, crazy formations, and mirages".
