They are chasing him, kicking him in heavy and flaming boots, throwing him against the walls, he feels the pains all over his body.
Raucous and evil voices resonate from the walls and radio.
He can no longer stand them, the voices that insult and offend him.
Henning T. rips two cables from the stereo, ties them to form a hanging knot, and fixes them on a hook on the ceiling.
It climbs in a horn and puts the knot around the neck.
Jump.
The rope is released.
What's a lesson to you, the voices shout in a choir that blows up the eardrums, "go to the clinic and make them heal you!"
Now, Henning T. is 40 years old and has experienced six acute psychoses, the last two years ago, the first almost 20 years ago.
The cause that produced it was LSD.
His diagnosis is schizo-affective-paranoid psychosis, he is also maniac-depressive, taking medication, against depression, mania, schizophrenia.
He has learned to live with his illness, for three years he has been married.
In psychosis I have experienced the most terrible anguish and the deepest despair, he says.
Hallucinations are a cruel reality
About one percent of the population falls ill at least once in the life of schizophrenia; in psychiatric clinics it is treated as the second most frequent disease after depression.
In an acute schizophrenic psychosis, most of the time those affected can no longer distinguish between the outside and the inner world, and fall into a state of overexcitement that can lead to hallucinations, delusions of greatness, disturbances in the relationship, or persecutory mania.
Especially widespread is hearing voices: voices that give orders, comment or dialogue.
Optical hallucinations are also common.
The affected person is no longer able to distinguish what is not important, the brain can no longer filter the disturbing signals, consciousness is flooded with impressions.
Like sleep, psychosis also opens the floodgates to a torrent of ideas and fantasies that come from the deepest layers of consciousness.
The perception of reality in psychosis is centered on the subject, says Professor Thomas Fuchs, chief physician at the general psychiatry clinic at Heidelberg University Hospital.
The schizophrenic is at the center of events, everything has a meaning addressed to him.
At the same time it enters into a passive role, as in a dream, is overwhelmed by events and cannot actively organize them.
That is why schizophrenics often feel threatened, controlled and manipulated.
In general it is not possible to adjust reality to them, hallucinations are a cruel reality, to wake up, impossible.
Having experienced a hallucination once in a lifetime
Unlike in a dream, Fuchs says, "the spatial and sensory structure of reality that are perceived in psychosis remain in principle as it is."
Paranoid thoughts and hallucinations are based on reality, the distance from experience takes place in reality.
For researchers still a question why our brain makes cabrioles.
According to Fuchs, states of emergency can lead anyone to lose touch with reality provisionally.
Not everyone develops a psychosis.
Apparently there is a genetic disposition for schizophrenia, but studies in twins have shown that in addition to genes there are also other determining factors.
Researchers assume that those affected suffer minimal brain damage.
We suspect that the neuronal maturity of the brain is affected at an early stage of development, such as through a mother’s viral disease during pregnancy, Fuchs explains.
But it is still unknown how this alteration of the neural system occurs, which also does not manifest itself at all for many years.
Also the influence of the environment plays an important role – stress or a traumatic experience can be the triggers of a psychosis when there is already a previous disposition.
Similarly, hallucinogenic drugs can cause a psychosis, as they interfere with the brain’s transmitter system.
