I think the brain is unoccupied and it is in charge of looking for entertainment.
Sarah K., the only child, was in a small fear of the other children and often played alone.
His hallucinations began when, at 13, he learned that the man he calls Dad since he was used to reason is not his biological father.
Since visual and acoustic hallucinations are active in the same areas of the brain that also process real impressions and noise, those affected like Sarah K. They find it difficult to distinguish between visions and reality. “Every experience,” says Kasten, “takes place in the brain, reality is projected there.
Hallucinations are equally images that the brain produces, that's why they seem so real."
Kasten also classifies nighttime fantasies as a form of hallucination.
Hallucinations of healthy people do not differ fundamentally from those of acute psychosis.
Unlike schizophrenics, psychically healthy people are able to recognize their visions as unreal.
Kasten therefore recommends that his patients appreciate their hallucinations as a special skill.
Limited situation between sleep and hallucination
In this world too focused on the conscious, imaginary experiences are usually pathologized, says Michael Schmidt-Degenhard, professor at Heidelberg and chief physician at the clinic of psychiatry and psychotherapy at Florence-Nightingale-Krankenhauses Hospital in Düsseldorf.
A psychosis is a hard and painful disease but it also entails something positive and creative – madness is a work of art of despair.
Schmidt-Degenhard has researched the so-called oneirism, a special form of consciousness, which is perceived as a dream.
Dream hallucinations are almost very complex and detailed dreams that the person who experiences them considers real and who subsequently cannot differentiate from being awake.
Onyrical conscious states arise in extreme situations associated with trauma or disease, such as in patients with polyradiculoneuropathy, who experience motor paralysis while fully conscious. die bei vollem Bewusstsein eine motorische Lähmung erleben.
According to Schmidt-Degenhardt, when a person is threatened by a loss of oneself or the world due to a total and permanent motor incapacity, it replaces a very dangerous real situation with a world of one’s own and imaginary that is decoupled from reality.
A form of boundary situation between sleep and hallucination.
Since it is not possible to overcome a situation in reality, there is a change of world, although the real situation is still present in the imagination.
An intensive way of giving meaning and interpretation to an unbearable situation in itself that our own capacity for creation allows us not to sink into the nothingness of loss of consciousness.
Everything is real, even later in memory
Also the art historian Peter Cornelius Claussen, from Zurich, describes his dreamlike experiences in his book Herzenwechsel as a life-saving action of the soul.
He was 49 years old, when his conscience embarked on trips of several days after a heart valve operation with heart transplant included, while his body was doomed to immobility in the intensive care station.
Claussen plunged into a world created by him and visited strange places of other times: he was bedridden, an older man aboard a sanatorium on a train, a robot was watching over his health.
It was seen in the high Middle Ages, surrounded by nobles who produced narcotics from blood.
A Greek man on a motorcycle kidnapped him in his home country, surfed on his hospital bed in the Alps with firn snow and found a Korean mobster.
It gives everything in these imaginary facts, everything is real, even later in the memories.
For Claussen, these inner journeys are fundamentally different from any dream.
Dreaming is a different state, thus describing your experience.
On the contrary, the memories of mental travel are, many years later, much clearer, even in irrelevant details.
Clearer and more intensive even than real experiences.
The intensity of this experience dilutes the horizon of the rest of our everyday experiences, adds the Schmidt-Degenhard psychiatrist.
Finally, oneirism, psychosis, hallucinations and drug use show how fragile the inner reproduction of the outer reality is, even when we are awake.
Each state of consciousness modification, sums up psychologist Kasten, "can lead to a deformation of what we call reality."
An experience that, on the other hand, can be completely enriching.
