Emergency braking aid is already mandatory
As with the anti-lock of ABS brakes and will happen with the ESP stability control, emergency braking aid systems will have to be a mandatory element in European cars.
In fact, they are already in all passenger cars and light commercial vehicles of new registration, while for the rest a period of lack is set until the end of February 2011.
The measure, imposed by the European Union, aims to increase the protection of pedestrians although, due to its way of working, it can also help to avoid many collisions by scope.
The emergency braking assistant does increase the pressure on the brakes in case of an emergency, which the system detects by the stomp that the driver gives.
But this one doesn't always keep that pressure until the end.
According to a study carried out by the car component manufacturer Bosch, a third of the drivers involved in an accident had not come to step on the brakes before the collision and half of them did not take advantage of the full force.
Up to 1,100 accidents
The intervention of the aid, on the other hand, requires the maximum to the braking system, reducing the distance that the car uses in stopping.
According to an EU study, if all cars were equipped with this type of element, up to 1,100 fatal accidents involving pedestrians could be avoided each year.
The reduction will be even greater – it is estimated that one in four accidents with human damage would be avoided – when the so-called intelligent emergency braking system is popularized.
In this case, the vehicle is equipped with a system that (through a radar or a camera) detects obstacles and warns the driver, in addition to acting slightly on the brakes.
If the driver reacts, it helps by increasing the pressure on the pedal, if necessary.
In case it does not react, and even if the collision is inevitable, the device exerts maximum effort to the brakes to minimize damage.
