Internet auction of crashed cars
Last October the Solera group bought Autoonline, an internet platform for the sale of cars such as motorcycles or special vehicles damaged.
The operation involved an outlay of 59.5 million euros for 85% of the company’s capital, which could be extended next year to the remaining 15%.
The objective of the acquisition was to offer more value-added services to its customers, with the possibility of accessing an immense international market.
This valuation and sales service is aimed exclusively at professionals in the sector, such as insurance companies, experts, rental companies, workshops, scrappers and professional sellers who must register before starting to carry out operations.
This platform was created in 1996 in Germany and manages more than 650,000 operations across Europe, 500,000 of them in Germany.
Among its main markets are Spain, Greece, Poland and Turkey.
The website currently has more than 1,500 registered sellers and 4,000 experts.
3,000 daily ads are managed and about 100 new ads are included in the Spanish market every day.
Under Spanish law, a car whose frame number has been discharged cannot recirculate, but certain undamaged parts can be used as a spare part.
Cars with historical value can register even if they have been discharged after some fary efforts.
Four-step workshop budget
With the Auda-Workshop tool, the company Audatex guarantees that the user gets a budget in just four steps: identify the vehicle, look for the replacement, create budget and generate budget.
Ease of use is an essential condition for these systems, especially to convince older professionals, who to a greater or lesser extent are usually more reluctant to use new management techniques.
The database includes 1,034 vehicles, which are 666 passenger cars, 109 SUVs, 137 motorcycles, 78 vans and 44 trucks.
Naturally, a computer with an internet connection is necessary for use.
Once the model to be repaired is identified by its frame number, a real graphic image of the model in question appears, and then the necessary replacement is selected.
The user can include variables such as labor price, surcharges or discounts, and then can print the quote to deliver to the customer.
AudaTaller is not a valuation tool like AudaPlus, but rather a catalog of references.
The main difference between the two systems is that workshop-oriented does not include estimated labor times.
The cost of using this tool for the workshop is 350 euros per year, which the client can finance.
Currently the company Audatex is working to make these images three-dimensional.
This is an innovation that mechanics see with very good eyes, since it will allow, for example, to select a door and turn it over to see the inner face.
